    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my tomato plants are looking kind of sickly. the leaves on the bottom are turning yellow and falling off. what do you think is going on?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It sounds like your tomato plants are experiencing a bit of a \"garden gremlin\" situation. The yellowing leaves and falling off can be a sign of nutrient deficiencies, overwatering, or even root bound conditions. I'd recommend checking the soil moisture and pH levels, as a sudden change in either can cause stress to the plants. You might also want to inspect the roots for any signs of root rot or other issues. \n\nIt's also possible that the plants are simply getting a bit too much competition from the surrounding foliage, a common problem in densely planted gardens. A bit of pruning and training might be in order to give the plants some breathing room. \n\nYou know, I've heard that some gardeners swear by using compost tea to give their plants a boost. It's a bit like a magic potion for your garden, but it's actually just a concentrated solution of beneficial microbes that help to break down nutrients and provide a natural fertilizer. \n\nIn any case, I'd recommend taking a closer look at your plants and seeing if you can identify the root cause of the problem. With a bit of TLC and some targeted care, you should be able to get your tomato plants back on track.",
